sample.title: No Nvidia Chips Needed! Amazon‚Äôs New AI Data Center For Anthropic Is Truly Massive
sample.description:
On 1,200 acres in Indiana, Amazon‚Äôs biggest AI data center is now operational, with half a million AWS Trainium2 chips entirely devoted to powering OpenAI rival Anthropic. Just over a year ago, the whole site was nothing but dirt and cornfields. Seven buildings are operating now, and once complete, the site will have around 30 buildings and consume some 2.2 gigawatts of power. CNBC went to the small town of New Carlisle, Indiana, to talk to locals who are worried about the impact on their community and electric bills - and to get a first ever on-camera tour inside what Amazon‚Äôs calling the largest cluster of non-Nvidia chips in the world. We also sat down with AWS CEO Matt Garman and Anthropic CPO Mike Krieger for more details on the partnership.

sample.title: Former Biden press secretary on how Democrats can win again | BBC Americast
sample.description:
Karine Jean-Pierre spent nearly three years as the public face of the Biden administration. As the White House Press Secretary and Senior Adviser to the president she spent her last few months battling questions about President Joe Biden‚Äôs mental and physical capabilities to do the job. Now she‚Äôs left the Democratic Party, saying that they unleashed a ‚Äúfiring squad‚Äù on Biden and forced him out of the 2024 presidential race. 

Justin speaks to her about her book ‚ÄòIndependent: A Look Inside a Broken White House Outside the Party Lines‚Äô, why she thinks the Democratic Party has lost its fight and her belief that the party are abandoning LGBTQ issues and migrants in their attempt to fight back against Republicans.

sample.title: How is Trump reacting to Putin‚Äôs nuclear tests? | BBC Ukrainecast
sample.description:
After an EU decision on the use of frozen Russian assets to aid Ukraine was postponed until December, discussion among European leaders returned to plans for a ceasefire this week. And the latest example of so-called nuclear 'sabre-rattling' by Vladimir Putin, forced Donald Trump to respond with a vague commitment of his own to resume US nuclear testing for the first time in decades.
 
On this edition of Ukrainecast, Jamie Coomarasamy and Vitaly Shevchenko are joined by BBC Verify's Olga Robinson and senior digital journalist Laura Gozzi, to answer your questions. Could Denmark and Sweden police the Baltic Sea? What happened to the Russian dam targeted by Ukraine? And are Russians facing discrimination from authorities in Europe?

sample.description:
US President Donald Trump and his Chinese counterpart Xi Jinping have agreed a one year truce deal.
 
On Thursday, the pair met for the first time in six years. 
 
China has agreed to suspend export control measures it had placed on rare earths for one year, while the US said it would drop part of the tariffs it has levied on Beijing over the flow of ingredients used in making fentanyl to the US.
 
But how long will this truce last?
